<font color="#FF0000">NO CONFUSION ABOUT THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan 11 12:16:40 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
No Confusion about the war<br><br>
JED and others<br><br>
Americans have always respected and honored their military men, those who served their country have been honored with medals, and to an extend certain privileges ( GI Bill etc.)<br><br>
All soldiers that have ever fought for their countries throughout the centuries have had the respect and honor, of their country. Those that were killed in battle their families were compensated in some form or another. Those wounded that suffered disabling wounds were likewise compensated to some degree for their efforts in protecting their fellow countrymen. All were honored, not so with Vietnam. Why?<br><br>
When I joined the USMC in December 1966, the Vietnam War at that time was still popular war, many Americans supported it saw it as a means to curb Communism. I volunteered for duty, proud to serve my country. This view of support prevailed for the first few years of the war. When protestor arose against the soldiers serving and the war in South East Asia many Americans rallied around the flagpole and formed their own counter-demonstration groups 1967-1968. <br><br>
When I went to war I had that type of support behind me and we fought a good clean war June 1967-July 1968. The term &quot;Duty war,&quot; was used during the French Indochina war, long before we were militarily involved, but it soon found its way into the media and the protestors mouth. Mid-way during my tour Marty a fellow machine gunner went on R&amp;R came back home and when he came back he reported four things of importance to us.<br><br>
1. Every girl was wearing mini-skirts<br>
2. Everything was psychedelic<br>
3. College students were protesting against the war.<br>
4. American citizens were protesting against the protestors<br><br>
Meanwhile, we were engaged in fighting hard corps communist soldiers. Chinese communist and Russian advisors among them, we also killed. There was no doubt in my mind as to who we were fighting. Not the local populace, or village locals but hard corps communist soldiers trained and bred in North Vietnam. All of their weapons were communist made. <br><br>
Before we went to Vietnam, we had been told that we would be fighting the Viet Cong, (VC stands for Vietnamese Communist), communist insurgents that were trying to overthrow the South Vietnamese government. Yes we removed citizens from their villages and removed rice from their homes. <br><br>
Operation Foster launched in November 1967 was done so, after the North Vietnamese Army rocketed DaNang with fifty 122-mm Soviet made rockets and after the NVA/VC launched vicious raids against civilian who had been re-settled in refuge camps. They killed innocent civilians for absolutely no reason other then to put fear in their hearts so that would not oppose the NVA in that area. <br><br>
Tom, you mentioned about some guilt assocaited with removing villagers and taking their rice. <br>
The South Vietnamese Army had been resettling their own people in refugee villages long before we entered into the war and I have no guilt feelings about doing that. <br>
During operation Foster we took out over 11,700 refugee out an area where they were literally at the mercy of the NVA, who killed, raped and took their rice and living essentials for their own needs. We recovered over 75 tons of US Polished rice, buried in the district headquarters in the central area of where we called Arizona territory. That rice had been donated by the Quakers, their markings on the bag. It was not destroyed most goods were never destroyed but transported to the South Vietnamese refugee camps and given to the people. Yes, we also burned down huts and villages but not while the people were in them as the NVA did.<br>
We burned them down when we found out they were used by the NVA, burned hooches where we found weapons, military and medical supplies in.  It was hard core NVA communist soldiers we fought against.<br><br>
Often when we went through the battlefield (Charlie played a good psychological war in the field and later in the streets of America, In Vietnam they worked in cell teams. Three men team where if one of them was wounded the other two immediately removed them from the field and another cell team replaced them), after a fire fight rarely did we find an enemies body. Tunnel complexes under villages ran for miles. When we did find some bodies often they had been riddled with 8-9 of our bullets. You see, they were almost always high on heroine which they took before they engaged us in battle. They would continue to fight even when they were already dead. Each of them carried their own black body bag to be quickly buried if they died. We fought at least six – seven major battles under these conditions while I was there. It was a different type of kamikaze warrior we were fighting in Nam. <br><br>
When I returned home, I was not met by protestors, that I believe I could have understood, that type of  hatred and I probably would have re-acted, letting off stream and that might have helped. No, what I encountered was something worst. It was the silence of the American people. A silence that reeked of mistrust and confusion.<br><br>
By July of 1968 the protestors, demonstrators and News media had weaken American resolve to support the American fighting men. There was silence on the bus as I went home in uniform and it spoke volumes to my heart. <br>
My own wife (ex-wife) wouldn’t come out to meet me in public, didn’t want to see me in uniform. The people stared at me, with the same stare I had seen on the faces of the South Vietnamese peasant’s when we removed them from the villages. Confused, bewildered and doubtful. No honor, no welcome home. It wasn’t until last February 1997, that someone finally said to me “Welcome Home.” <br><br>
Something was wrong and so for 30 years I remained silent, for 30 years every Marine I served with remained silent. We didn’t know what had happened, we didn’t ask for much. We just went on with our lives. We were shamed for having done our duty.<br>
Can you imagine the treatment wounded and disabled returning Vietnam veterans received at the VA hospitals that was mostly staffed by many that could care less about the Vietnam veteran. <br><br>
We had American support when we left and were looked at less then honorable when we returned. What had we done? We had merely served our country and received no gratitude from them in return. Why? <br><br>
Because public opinion of the war changed, while many still supported our efforts there, what had changed was that Americans were confused about the war and choose instead of fighting the protestors to remain silent and in the background and here is where Communism won the war at home in America. Where communist and social do gooders who saw funds they wanted for themselves being directed toward the war effort so they arose in protest. So Charlie, communist propaganda effectively used the anti-war protestors, demonstrators, civil and social unrest and druggies, and every rift rat that was against our form of government to do strike out from within America and they were highly effective. <br><br>
A lot of misinformation was given out and the public soon had doubts and that is all that communism wanted to occur in America and in this they were highly successful. We may have won every battle in Nam but we lost the war in the streets of America. The Johnson, Diem and Minh administrations were all corrupt, we know this but still when it comes down to it. It was communism we fought and it was communist soldiers I killed in battle. I have no regrets for that. It was communist that caused the pain and heartache in BOTH North and South Vietnam. <br><br>
Unfortunately we felt that same rejection from WWII and Korean Veterans who reacted to the news more so then others; they had nothing to compare Vietnam to. “We all tend to oppose what we don’t understand,” as a result the American Vietnam veteran suffered the most. Suffered disgrace for having done his duty. I still believe that PTSD is more of a by-product of that rejection then what we experienced in Vietnam and that is the reason why for 30 years I never shared that war with anyone until now, here on this site and in my book. <br><br>
I’m Cook Barela and those are my thoughts.<br>

